451. Sort Characters By Frequency
Problem

Given a string s, sort it in decreasing order based on character frequency.

Example
Input: s = "tree"
Output: "eert"

Explanation:

e -> 2 times
r -> 1 time
t -> 1 time

So characters with higher frequency come first.

Approach 1: Brute Force (Repeated Max Frequency Scan)
Intuition
Count frequencies using HashMap.
Repeatedly find the character with maximum frequency.
Append it frequency times.
Mark its frequency as 0.

Java
class Solution {
    public String frequencySort(String s) {

        HashMap<Character, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();

        for(char ch : s.toCharArray()) {
            map.put(ch, map.getOrDefault(ch, 0) + 1);
        }

        StringBuilder ans = new StringBuilder();

        while(!map.isEmpty()) {

            char maxChar = ' ';
            int maxFreq = 0;

            for(Map.Entry<Character, Integer> entry : map.entrySet()) {
                if(entry.getValue() > maxFreq) {
                    maxFreq = entry.getValue();
                    maxChar = entry.getKey();
                }
            }

            for(int i = 0; i < maxFreq; i++) {
                ans.append(maxChar);
            }

            map.remove(maxChar);
        }

        return ans.toString();
    }
}
Complexity
Time: O(n²)
Space: O(n)
Approach 2: Sorting by Frequency
Intuition
Count frequencies.
Store characters in a list.
Sort based on frequency descending.
Build answer.

Java
class Solution {
    public String frequencySort(String s) {

        HashMap<Character, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();

        for(char ch : s.toCharArray()) {
            map.put(ch, map.getOrDefault(ch, 0) + 1);
        }

        List<Character> list = new ArrayList<>(map.keySet());

        list.sort((a, b) -> map.get(b) - map.get(a));

        StringBuilder ans = new StringBuilder();

        for(char ch : list) {
            for(int i = 0; i < map.get(ch); i++) {
                ans.append(ch);
            }
        }

        return ans.toString();
    }
}
Complexity
Time: O(n log n)
Space: O(n)
Approach 3: Max Heap (Most Common Interview Solution)
Intuition

Store characters in a max heap according to frequency.

Highest frequency character comes first.
Remove and append until heap becomes empty.

Java
class Solution {
    public String frequencySort(String s) {

        HashMap<Character, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();

        for(char ch : s.toCharArray()) {
            map.put(ch, map.getOrDefault(ch, 0) + 1);
        }

        PriorityQueue<Character> pq =
                new PriorityQueue<>((a, b) ->
                        map.get(b) - map.get(a));

        pq.addAll(map.keySet());

        StringBuilder ans = new StringBuilder();

        while(!pq.isEmpty()) {

            char ch = pq.poll();

            for(int i = 0; i < map.get(ch); i++) {
                ans.append(ch);
            }
        }

        return ans.toString();
    }
}
Dry Run

Input:

s = "tree"

Frequency Map:

t -> 1
r -> 1
e -> 2

Max Heap:

[e, t, r]

Poll:

e -> append "ee"
t -> append "t"
r -> append "r"

Result:

"eetr"

("eert" is also valid)

Complexity
Time: O(n log k)
Space: O(k)

k = unique characters

Approach 4: Bucket Sort (Optimal)
Intuition

Maximum frequency of any character can be at most n.

Create buckets:

bucket[frequency] = characters with that frequency

Traverse buckets from high frequency to low frequency.

Java
class Solution {
    public String frequencySort(String s) {

        HashMap<Character, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();

        for(char ch : s.toCharArray()) {
            map.put(ch, map.getOrDefault(ch, 0) + 1);
        }

        List<Character>[] bucket =
                new ArrayList[s.length() + 1];

        for(char ch : map.keySet()) {

            int freq = map.get(ch);

            if(bucket[freq] == null) {
                bucket[freq] = new ArrayList<>();
            }

            bucket[freq].add(ch);
        }

        StringBuilder ans = new StringBuilder();

        for(int i = bucket.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {

            if(bucket[i] != null) {

                for(char ch : bucket[i]) {

                    for(int j = 0; j < i; j++) {
                        ans.append(ch);
                    }
                }
            }
        }

        return ans.toString();
    }
}
Dry Run

Input:

s = "tree"

Frequency:

t -> 1
r -> 1
e -> 2

Buckets:

bucket[1] = [t,r]
bucket[2] = [e]

Traverse from end:

bucket[2] -> "ee"
bucket[1] -> "t" + "r"

Result:

"eetr"
Complexity
Time: O(n)
Space: O(n)
Interview Summary
Approach	Time	Space
Repeated Max Scan	O(n²)	O(n)
Sorting	O(n log n)	O(n)
Max Heap	O(n log k)	O(k)
Bucket Sort (Optimal)	O(n)	O(n)
Pattern
String
   ↓
Frequency Map
   ↓
Top Frequent Characters
   ↓
Build Result String
Key Takeaway
Max Heap → Most common interview solution.
Bucket Sort → Optimal solution (O(n)).
Same pattern as LeetCode 347 Top K Frequent Elements, but here we return a sorted string instead of top k elements.
